concept_explanation.the_rules:
**4 Rules for calculating Big-O:**

```java
// RULE 1: Drop constants
// This is O(2n) = O(n) — the 2 doesn't matter at scale
for (int x : arr) sum += x;         // n ops
for (int x : arr) product *= x;     // n ops
// Total: 2n → O(n)

// RULE 2: Drop non-dominant terms
// O(n² + n) → O(n²) — n² dominates
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)         // n ops
    for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {}  // n ops each → n²
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {}      // n ops → irrelevant
// Total: n² + n → O(n²)

// RULE 3: Different inputs = different variables
for (int a : arrA) {}  // O(a)
for (int b : arrB) {}  // O(b)
// Total: O(a + b), NOT O(n)

// RULE 4: Nested loops = multiply
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)         // n
    for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {}  // × n = n²
```

